natural problem: The height of a ball when it is thrown off a cliff can be represented by the equation $h=45-7t-6t^2$, where $t$ is time in seconds. In how many seconds will the ball reach a height of 25 feet?
natural solution: If we plug in 25 for $h$, we get \begin{align} 25& =45-7t-6t^2 \\\Rightarrow\qquad 6t^2+7t-20& =0 \\\Rightarrow\qquad (3t-4)(2t+5)& =0 \end{align}The two possible values of $t$ are $\frac43$, and $-\frac52$.
Since the time can only be a positive value, the answer must be $\boxed{\frac43}$.

theorem
fixes h t :: real
assumes h0 : "\<forall> t. h = 45 - 7 * t - 6 * t powr 2"
and h1 : "h = 25"
shows  "t = 4/3"
